<H1>
The Extremely Condensed History of Computing</H1>
<A NAME="1"></A>
<H3>
"It Weaves Algebraic Patterns": Abacuses, Looms, and Arithmetic Engines
(c.3000 B.C. to c.1870)</H3>
<A HREF="http://www.qi-journal.com/abacus.html"><IMG SRC="abacus.gif"  ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
The need for counting has always been with us: trade and barter, sizing
up the enemy's army, describing the size of a herd, economic planning (the
Egyptians had sophisticated harvesting timetables). This ubiquitous need
led to the Sumerian counting tablet using small stones (<I>calculi</I>),
the Chinese <A HREF="http://www.qi-journal.com/abacus.html">abacus</A>,
and numeration systems (<B>Scavenger hunt:</B> who invented the zero?).
Social and economic development after the Dark Ages brought the need for
more complicated and time-consuming computations: multiplication and division,
raising to powers, taking roots. Inventors responded with the logarithms,
Napier's Bones, and the slide rule (an early analog computer); and with
various mechanical calculating machines, culminating in the dazzlingly
complex designs of the eccentric genius Charles Babbage and his protege
Ada Lovelace. Babbage's insight, inspired by Jacquard's punch-card-controlled
weaving loom, was that machines could be made to perform an <I>arbitrary</I>
sequence of manipulations of numerical quantities: the genesis of the <I>stored
program</I> concept.
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><A HREF="http://www.cbi.umn.edu/charles.htm"><IMG SRC="babbage.jpg"  ALIGN=LEFT></A>&nbsp;<A HREF="http://www.scottlan.edu/lriddle/women/love.htm"><IMG SRC="lovelace.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT></A>
<I>Inventors/Engineers:</I>
<BR>Charles Babbage, Ada Lovelace

<P><I>A First:</I>
<BR>First Government grant for computer science research

