<HR><A NAME="2"></A>
<H3>
The <A HREF="http://www2.lib.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/www2/WEBSTER.sh?word=apotheosis">Apotheosis</A>
of Mechanical Computers (1890-1940)</H3>
<A HREF="http://www.computer-museum.org/collections/hollerith.html"><IMG SRC="hollpunch.gif"  ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
The U.S. of the late 1800's was the world's industrial and economic leader,
with a laissez-faire capitalist ambience that encouraged an unprecedented
wave of innovation and invention....and a population exploding so rapidly
that census tabulation could barely be finished in time for the next census.
It was in this atmosphere that the energetic and entrepreneurial <A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/57.html">Herman
Hollerith</A> patented his punch-card reader and tabulating machine, which
the U.S. Government used for the 1890 and 1900 censuses and which made
Hollerith a millionaire. (<B>Scavenger hunt:</B> What year was the last
U.S. Census to use punch-card technology, and what replaced the punch cards
after that?)

<P>Meanwhile, German inventor Konrad Zuse made notable improvements to
mechanical calculators (incorporation of Boole's binary logic, programmability
using paper tapes), but they were eclipsed by&nbsp;<A HREF="http://www.arts.ucsb.edu:80/HAC/his.comp/1900-1929/1925.html"><IMG SRC="diff_anlz.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT></A>two
huge machines: the Differential Analyzer, built by Vannevar Bush and his
colleagues at MIT and operational by 1925, and the Mark I, built at Harvard
and IBM under the direction of Howard Aiken. Both were paragons of electromechanical
computing---and technological dead ends. For in heartland Iowa and Philadelphia,
the ideas behind the nearest predecessor to today's electronic computer
were already being developed. The inventors would deliver to the military
the next-generation electronic computer and launch a new industry, only
to be overtaken, ironically, by the descendant of Hollerith's CTR Company:
<A HREF="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</A>.

<P>&nbsp;
<BR><A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/57.html"><IMG SRC="hollerith.gif"  ALIGN=LEFT></A>&nbsp;<IMG SRC="vbush.jpg" >
<I>Inventors/Entrepreneur/Visionary:</I>
<BR>Herman Hollerith, Vannevar Bush

<P><I>A First:</I>
<BR>Hollerith's CTR Company (Computing-Tabulating-Recording), the first
high-tech startup to make its founder a millionaire.

