<HR><A NAME="3"></A>
<H3>
ENIAC and UNIVAC: The Computer Is Born (1940-1955)</H3>
<A HREF="http://www.library.upenn.edu/special/gallery/mauchly/jwmintro.html"><IMG SRC="eniac.jpg"  ALIGN=LEFT></A>By
1937, America's eventual involvement in World War II seemed inevitable.
But Bush's Differential Analyzer took nearly a month to compute complete
ballistic trajectory tables; so the Army, desperate for faster computers,
awarded a contract in 1943 to the University of Pennsylvania. At Penn's
Moore School of Engineering, recent faculty hire John Mauchly and 21-year-old
graduate student J. Presper Eckert had proposed a high-speed vacuum-tube
calculating machine. Working against the opinion of the nation's most influential
researchers and military strategists, Eckert and Mauchly's team produced
ENIAC (Electronic Numerical Integrator And Calculator), the first general-purpose
electronic digital computer, ushering in the computer age.&nbsp;<A HREF="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/detail/1951-univac.html"><IMG SRC="univac_small.gif" HEIGHT=72 WIDTH=80 ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
Little did they know that the short-lived Eckert-Mauchly Computer Company,
which begat UNIVAC (the first commercial general-purpose electronic computer),
would be quickly absorbed into the most bitter and protracted patent feud
in computer history. At issue: Mauchly's conversations with John Vincent
Atanasoff, an Iowa State professor who had been playing with vacuum-tube
binary circuits; engineering dean Paul Brainerd's ideas about patent policies
for Moore School research; and the unofficial early "evangelism" publication
describing stored-program computers by brilliant and flamboyant mathematician
John von Neumann.

<P>&nbsp;
<BR><IMG SRC="mauchly_eckert.jpg"  ALIGN=LEFT>&nbsp;<A HREF="http://nano.xerox.com/nanotech/vonNeumann.html"><IMG SRC="vonneumann.jpg"  ALIGN=TOP></A>
<BR clear="both"><I>Inventors/Entrepreneurs/Scientists:</I>
<BR>John Mauchly and J. Presper Eckert, John von Neumann, John Vincent
Atanasoff

<P><I>A First:</I>
<BR>First legal dispute regarding commercial and patent rights to Government-sponsored
University research.

<P><B>Readings:</B> Much of this material comes from the <A HREF="http://www.seas.upenn.edu/~museum/">ENIAC
Virtual Museum at the University of Pennsylvania.</A>
