<HR><A NAME="4"></A>
<H3>
IBM and the Seven Dwarfs (1955-1970)</H3>
<A HREF="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/detail/1947-point.html"><IMG SRC="xistor.gif" HEIGHT=97 WIDTH=72 ALIGN=RIGHT></A><A HREF="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/1947/1947-point.html">
</A>UNIVAC may have been the first commercial computer, but by the early
1960's IBM's hegemony in business computers was undisputed. (<I>Personal</I>
computer? What's that?) A number of companies made a living off the crumbs,
building accessories that worked with IBM's equipment; but IBM quickly
became the undisputed leader in business computer sales. IBM's success
was due to its legendary sales force and the influence and leadership of
Thomas J. Watson Jr., who inherited presidency of the company from his
father in 1952 and whose innate grasp of computers (he was, after all,
of the "ENIAC generation") provided his vision for IBM's future, with his
father's grudging consent.

<P>&nbsp;But all that was about to change. The 1947 invention of the solid-state
transistor by Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley at AT&amp;T Bell Labs, a
tremendous improvement over the vacuum tube, had already made computers
cheaper, smaller, faster and more reliable. But the brainchild of two inventors
working independently, Jack Kilby and Bob Noyce, was about to take the
game to a whole new level: the <I>integrated circuit</I> combined both
transistorized computer logic and "glue" circuitry on a single silicon
chip.
<BR>
<table>
<tr>
<td align="top">
<A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/index.html"><IMG SRC="TJW_Sr.jpg"
ALIGN=top></A>&nbsp;<A
HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/5.html"><IMG
SRC="bardeen.jpg" align="top"></A>
</td>
<td>
<I>Entrepreneurs/Scientists:</I>
<BR>Thomas J. Watson, John Bardeen, William Shockley, Walter Brattain
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><I>Two Firsts:</I>
<UL>
<LI>
IBM uses the FUD tactic (Fear, Uncertainty and Doubt) to quash upstart
competitor Control Data.</LI>

<LI>
Shockley Semiconductor founded as the first company in what would become
Silicon Valley. Though long defunct, virtually every high-tech Silicon
Valley company, including Fairchild, Intel, Hewlett-Packard, trace their
lineage directly to Shockley.</LI>
</UL>
&nbsp;

</td>
</tr>
</table>
