<HR><A NAME="5"></A>
<H3>
Not Just for Number Crunching Anymore (1955-1970)</H3>
As computers became more powerful, people began to think of new ways of
using them, completely unlike the "number crunching" for which they were
originally intended. Steve Russell, a graduate student at MIT, demonstrated
the archetype of all video games, Spacewar, in 1962.&nbsp;<A HREF="http://www.cs.orst.edu/~crowl/history/"><IMG SRC="spacewar.jpg"  ALIGN=RIGHT></A>
Doug Engelbart invented the mouse in 1964 at <A HREF="http://parc.xerox.com">Xerox
PARC</A>, just one year after Ivan Sutherland had demonstrated Sketchpad,
the first use of computer graphics. Admiral Grace Murray Hopper built the
first compiler for a computer programming language, allowing programmers
to concentrate their programming effort on the problem being solved rather
than arcane machine details; the rapid development of languages like BASIC,
FORTRAN and COBOL allowed programming to evolve into a discipline as rich
and complex in its own right as computer design, and sparked renewed interest
in the theoretical analysis of algorithms and computability, based on the
pioneering theoretical work of the genius Alan Turing. In 1968, the NATO
Science Committee Conference coined the term <I>software engineering</I>
and the new field was officially born.

<P><A HREF="http://users.ox.ac.uk/~wadh0249/Turing.html"><IMG SRC="turing.jpg" ></A><A HREF="http://users.ox.ac.uk/~wadh0249/Turing.html">&nbsp;<A HREF="http://www2.bootstrap.org/dce-bio.htm"><IMG SRC="engelbart.jpg" ></A></A><A HREF="http://www2.bootstrap.org/dce-bio.htm">&nbsp;<A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Hopper.Danis.html"><IMG SRC="hopper.gif" ></A></A>
<BR><B>Scientists/Visionaries:</B>: Alan Turing, Doug Engelbart, Grace
Murray Hopper

<P><B>A First:</B> First visionary glimpses of mouse-and-windows graphical
interfaces, hypertext, and video games.
<BR><B>Readings for Apr 30:</B>
<UL>
