<HR><A NAME="6"></A>
<H3>
"A Computer On Every Desktop": Computing for the Masses (1970-1980)</H3>
A quiet revolution had been brewing since the invention of the solid state
transistor at Bell Labs in 1947 and the subsequent invention of the <I>integrated
circuit</I> by Bob Noyce and Jack Kilby, working independently and at separate
companies. Cheaper, less power-hungry, and more reliable than its primitive
ancestor the vacuum tube, the IC transformed the landscape for computer
design. Engineer and entrepreneur Ken Olsen seized the opportunity early,
and built the hugely successful Digital Equipment Corp. around <I>minicomputers</I>
that even modest businesses could afford. (The fabulously successful PDP-8
is the machine on which the UNIX operating system was born, and its successor
the VAX had sold more units than any machine in history until the IBM PC.)
(??) But what really turned the tide at Noyce's newly-formed Intel (for
<B>int</B>egrated <B>el</B>ectronics)was Ted Hoff's invention of the <I>microprocessor</I>,
essentially a complete computer on a single chip ("just add memory"). Now,
anyone with a few dollars could buy a microprocessor and build a small
computer. And build they did: when Steve Wozniak showed off his contraption
to the now-legendary Homebrew Computer Club in Silicon Valley, his entrepreneurial
partner Steve Jobs knew they had a winner. The Apple II was not the world's
first microcomputer, but with software wizards Dan Bricklin and Bob Frankston's
revolutionary program VisiCalc, the Apple II was the first to enjoy success
because of a <I>Killer App</I>. The writing was on the wall: "None will
survive the attack of the killer micros!"
<BR>&nbsp;

<P><B>Inventors/Entrepreneurs:</B> Marcian E. "Ted" Hoff, Steve Jobs and
Steve Wozniak, Bob Bricklin and Dan Frankston
<BR><B>Readings:</B>
