<B>Highly recommended optional readings:</B>
<UL>

  <LI>
       <A HREF="http://www.herring.com/mag/issue23/accidental.html">The Accidental
       Entrepreneur</A>: Red Herring's interview with Gordon Moore, cofounder
       of Intel</LI>

  <LI>
       The <A HREF="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/">Intel Museum</A> online.
       Check out especially the
       <A HREF="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/25anniv/">25th
       Anniversary</A> of the microprocessor, and the
       <A HREF="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/25anniv/iwh/iwh_main.htm">Interact
       With History</A> exhibit, which lets you "relive" the founding of Intel
       and the invention of the microprocessor.</LI>

</UL>

<HR>
<BR><A NAME="7"></A>
<H3>
You <I>Can</I> Take It With You: The Big Shrink (1990-1997)</H3>
&nbsp;
<BR>

Moore's Law soon made it realistic to think about "portable" computers.
The first such was the
<a
href="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/detail/1981-osborne.html">Osborne
I</a>,
produced in 1981, which weighed 24 pounds and cost $1,795.

<HR>

<P><A NAME="8"></A>
<H3>
"Insanely Great": User Friendly Interfaces and The Computer That Changed
Everything (1980-1990)</H3>
<B>Readings:</B>
<UL>
<LI>
<I>Triumph of the Nerds</I>. This video series (three 30-minute episodes)
is available in the Cal VIEW office, 205 McLaughlin Hall. It's based on
Robert X. Cringely's book <I>Accidental Empires</I>.</LI>
</UL>

