<h1>The Extremely Condensed History of Computing</h1>

<a name="1">
<h3>"It Weaves Algebraic Patterns": Abacuses, Looms, and Arithmetic
Engines (c.3000 B.C. to c.1870)</h3> 

<a href="http://www.qi-journal.com/abacus.html"> <img align="right"
src="gifs/abacus.gif"></a> The need for counting has always been with
us: trade and barter, sizing up the enemy's army, describing the size of
a herd, economic planning (the Egyptians had sophisticated harvesting
timetables).  This ubiquitous need led to the Sumerian counting tablet
using small stones (<i>calculi</i>), the Chinese <a
href="http://www.qi-journal.com/abacus.html">abacus</a>, and numeration
systems (<b>Scavenger hunt:</b> who invented the zero?).  Social and
economic development after the Dark Ages brought the need for more
complicated and time-consuming computations: multiplication and
division, raising to powers, taking roots.  Inventors responded with the
logarithms, Napier's Bones, and the slide rule (an early analog
computer); and with various mechanical calculating machines, culminating
in the dazzlingly complex designs of the eccentric genius Charles
Babbage and his protege Ada Lovelace.  Babbage's insight, inspired by
Jacquard's punch-card-controlled weaving loom, was that machines could
be made to perform an <i>arbitrary</i> sequence of manipulations of
numerical quantities: the genesis of the <i>stored program</i> concept.
<p>

<br>
<A HREF="http://www.cbi.umn.edu/charles.htm"><img src="gifs/babbage.jpg"
align="left"></a> 
<A HREF="http://www.scottlan.edu/lriddle/women/love.htm"><img
src="gifs/lovelace.gif" align="left"></a> 
<i>Inventors/Engineers:</i><br>
Charles Babbage, Ada Lovelace
<br><br>
<i>A First:</i><br>
First Government grant for computer science research

<br clear="left"><br>

<B>Reading:</b>
<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Babbage.html">A brief
       biography of Charles Babbage</a>
  <li> <a
       href="http://www.educom.edu/educom.review/review.96/mar.apr/freeman.html">Ada and the Analytical Engine</a>
  <li> <A HREF="http://orca.ucd.ie/~timf/ihpssay.html">A Scientific
       History of Mechanical Calculating Devices to 1850</A>, by Tim
       Foster, University College Dublin.
  <li> <a href="prehistory.html"><b>Questions for class discussion</b></a>
</ul>

<hr>
<a name="2">
<h3>The <a href="http://nqcd.lanl.gov/WEBSTER?apotheosis">Apotheosis</a>
of Mechanical Computers (1890-1940)</h3> 

<a href="http://www.computer-museum.org/collections/hollerith.html"><img
src="gifs/hollpunch.gif" align="right"></a> The U.S. of the late 1800's
was the world's industrial and economic leader, with a laissez-faire
capitalist ambience that encouraged an unprecedented wave of innovation
and invention....and a population exploding so rapidly that census
tabulation could barely be finished in time for the next census.  It was
in this atmosphere that the energetic and entrepreneurial <a
href="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/57.html">Herman Hollerith</a>
patented his punch-card reader and tabulating machine, which the
U.S. Government used for the 1890 and 1900 censuses and which made
Hollerith a millionaire.  (<b>Scavenger hunt:</b> What year was the last
U.S. Census to use punch-card technology, and what replaced the punch
cards after that?)  <br clear="left"> <br>Meanwhile, German inventor
Konrad Zuse made notable 
improvements to mechanical calculators (incorporation of Boole's binary
logic, programmability using paper tapes), but they were eclipsed by
<A
HREF="http://www.arts.ucsb.edu:80/HAC/his.comp/1900-1929/1925.html"><img
align="left" src="gifs/diff_anlz.gif"></a>two
huge machines: the Differential Analyzer, built by
Vannevar Bush and his colleagues at MIT and operational by 1925, and the
Mark I, built at Harvard and IBM under the direction of Howard Aiken.
Both were paragons of electromechanical computing---and technological
dead ends.  For in heartland Iowa and Philadelphia, the ideas
behind the nearest predecessor to today's electronic computer were
already  being
developed.  The inventors would deliver to the military the
next-generation electronic computer and launch a new industry, only to
be overtaken, ironically, by the descendant of Hollerith's CTR Company:
<a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a>.<p>

<br>
<A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/57.html"><img
align="left" src="gifs/hollerith.gif"></A>
<img src="gifs/vbush.jpg">
<i>Inventors/Entrepreneur/Visionary:</i><br>
Herman Hollerith, Vannevar Bush
<br><br>
<i>A First:</i><br>
Hollerith's CTR Company (Computing-Tabulating-Recording), the first
high-tech 
startup to make its founder a millionaire.
<br clear="left">
<br>
<B>Readings:</b>
<ul>
  <li> <A HREF="http://tdi.uregina.ca/~complit/holler.html">A brief
       biography of Herman Hollerith</A>
  <li> <A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Zuse.html">A brief
       biography of Konrad Zuse</A> (you can skip the "awards and
       honors" section)
<!--   <li> <a href="lecture_notes/hollerith_notes.html">Armando's notes on -->
<!--        Hollerith and Zuse</a> -->
  <li> <A HREF="http://ftp.arl.mil/~mike/comphist/61ordnance/chap1.html">
       Differential Analyzer</A>, from <i>Electronic Computers Within
       the Ordnance Corps</i> (start reading at "In 1925, at the
       Massachusetts Institute of Technology...", to read about the
       Differential Analyzer)
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.si.edu/resource/tours/comphist/eckert.htm#tc4">Some
       background on the Harvard/IBM Mark I</A>, from an interview with
       J. Presper Eckert, who we'll meet next time
  <li> <a href="http://bavard.fourmilab.ch/documents/univac/cards.html">Virtual
       Punch Card Gallery &amp; Museum</a> (slow link)
  <li> <b><a href="mechanical.html">Questions for class discussion</a></b>
</ul>

<hr>
<a name="3">
<h3>ENIAC and UNIVAC: The Computer Is Born (1940-1955)</h3>

<a href="http://www.library.upenn.edu/special/gallery/mauchly/jwmintro.html">
<img align="left" src="gifs/eniac.jpg"></a>By 1937, America's eventual
involvement in World War II seemed 
inevitable.  But Bush's Differential Analyzer took nearly a month to
compute complete ballistic trajectory tables; so the Army, desperate for
faster computers, awarded a contract in 1943 to the University of
Pennsylvania.  At Penn's Moore School of Engineering, recent
faculty hire John Mauchly and 21-year-old graduate student J. Presper
Eckert had proposed a high-speed vacuum-tube calculating machine.
Working against the opinion of the nation's most influential researchers
and military strategists, Eckert and Mauchly's team produced ENIAC
(Electronic Numerical Integrator And Calculator), the first
general-purpose electronic digital computer, ushering in the computer
age.  <a href="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/1951/1951.html"><img
align="right" src="gifs/univac_small.gif"></a> Little did they know that
the short-lived Eckert-Mauchly Computer Company, which begat UNIVAC (the
first commercial general-purpose electronic computer), would be quickly
absorbed into the most bitter and protracted patent feud in computer
history.  At issue: Mauchly's conversations with John Vincent Atanasoff,
an Iowa State professor who had been playing with vacuum-tube binary
circuits; engineering dean Paul Brainerd's ideas about patent policies
for Moore School research; and the unofficial early "evangelism"
publication describing stored-program computers by brilliant and
flamboyant mathematician John von Neumann.<p>


<br>
<img align="left" src="gifs/mauchly_eckert.jpg">
<A HREF="http://nano.xerox.com/nanotech/vonNeumann.html">
<img align="top" src="gifs/vonneumann.jpg"></A>
<br><i>Inventors/Entrepreneurs/Scientists:</i><br>
John Mauchly and J. Presper Eckert, John von Neumann, John Vincent Atanasoff
<br clear="left"><br>
<i>A First:</i><br>
First legal dispute regarding commercial and patent rights to
Government-sponsored University research.

<br clear="left"><br>

<B>Reading:</b> Much of this material comes from the <A
HREF="http://www.seas.upenn.edu/~museum/">ENIAC Virtual Museum at
the University of Pennsylvania.</a>
<ul>
  <li> <A
       HREF="http://www.library.upenn.edu/special/gallery/mauchly/jwmintro.html">John W. Mauchly and the Development of the ENIAC Computer</A>.  This online
       exhibit is <i>excellent</i> and contains a lot of <i>extremely
       important</i> background information.  Read carefully!
  <li> Brief biography of <A
       HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/VonNeumann.html">John von Neumann</A>
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.upenn.edu/almanac/v42/n18/eniac.html">A Short
       History of the Second American Revolution</A> (brief history of ENIAC)
  <li> <A HREF="http://ftp.arl.mil/~mike/comphist/96gore/">The
       Technology Challenge: How Can America Spark Private
       Innovation?</a>  Delivered by Vice President Al Gore at ENIAC's
       50th Birthday celebration.
  <li> Meanwhile back on the farm, <A
       HREF="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/1947/1947-point.html">the
       solid-state transistor</A> is invented in 1947 by scientists
       John Bardeen, Walter Brattain, and William Shockley at AT&amp;T
       Bell Labs.  More about
       this next time!
  <li> <a href="eniac.html"><b>Questions for class discussion</b></a>
</ul>

<b>Highly recommended optional reading:</b>
<ul>
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.computer.org/pubs/annals/a3013/a3013.htm">The
       Women of ENIAC</A>
</ul>

<br clear="left"><hr>
<a name="4">
<h3>IBM and the Seven Dwarfs (1955-1970)</h3>

<a href="http://www.tcm.org/history/timeline/1947/1947-point.html">
<img align="right" src="gifs/xistor.gif">
</a>
UNIVAC may have been the first commercial computer, but by the early
1960's IBM's hegemony in business computers was undisputed.
(<i>Personal</i> computer?  What's that?)  A number of companies made a
living off the crumbs, building accessories that worked with IBM's
equipment; but IBM quickly became the undisputed leader in business
computer sales.  IBM's success was due to its legendary sales force and the
influence and leadership of Thomas
J. Watson Jr., who inherited presidency of the company from his father
in 1952 and whose innate grasp of computers (he was, after all, of the
"ENIAC generation") provided his vision for IBM's future, with his
father's grudging consent.<p>
But all that was about to change.  The 1947 invention
of the solid-state transistor
by Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley at AT&amp;T
Bell Labs, a tremendous improvement over the vacuum tube, had already
made computers cheaper, smaller, faster and more reliable.  But the
brainchild of two inventors working independently, Jack Kilby and Bob
Noyce, was about to take the game to a whole new level: the
<i>integrated circuit</i> combined both transistorized computer logic
and "glue" circuitry on a single silicon chip.  
<br>
<A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/index.html"><img
align="left" src="gifs/TJW.Sr.jpg"></A>
<a href="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/5.html"><img align="left"
src="gifs/bardeen.jpg"></a>
<i>Entrepreneurs/Scientists:</i><br>
Thomas J. Watson, John Bardeen, William Shockley, Walter Brattain
<br><br clear="left"><br>
<i>Two Firsts:</i>
<ul>
  <li> IBM uses the FUD tactic (Fear, Uncertainty and Doubt) to quash upstart
       competitor Control Data.
  <li> Shockley Semiconductor founded as the first company in what would
       become Silicon Valley.  Though long defunct, virtually every high-tech
       Silicon Valley company, including Fairchild, Intel, Hewlett-Packard,
       trace their lineage directly to Shockley.
</ul>

<br clear="left"><br>
<b>Reading:</b>
<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/UNIVAC.Weston.html">UNIVAC,
       The Paul Revere of the Computer Revolution</a>.  By K. Ryan
       Weston, a student at Virginia Tech.
  <li> <a href="dwarf.html">Armando's notes</a> on UNIVAC, IBM, FUD, and
       the Dwarfs.
  <li> <a href="http://bavard.fourmilab.ch/documents/univac/index.html">UNIVAC
       memories</a> and the UNIVAC corporate family tree
  <li> <a href="http://www.kzoo.edu/~k93gp01/wat.jr.html">Brief
       biography of Thomas J. Watson, Jr.</a>
  <li> National Inventors Hall of Fame:
       <A HREF="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/5.html">John
       Bardeen, Walter Brattain, William Shockley</A>
  <li> <a href="patent.html">What some prominent inventors and
       scientists have to say</a> regarding the patent system and patent
       attorneys.
  <li> <b><a href="dwarf_questions.html">Questions for class
       discussion</a></b> 
</ul>
<br clear="left"><hr>
<a name="5">
<h3>Not Just for Number Crunching Anymore (1955-1970)</h3>

d296 228
a523 205
originally intended.  Steve Russell, a graduate student at MIT,
demonstrated the archetype of all video games, Spacewar, in 1962.
<a href="http://www.cs.orst.edu/~crowl/history/">
<img align="right" src="gifs/spacewar.jpg"></a>
Doug
Engelbart invented the mouse in 1964 at <a
href="http://parc.xerox.com">Xerox PARC</a>, just one year after Ivan
Sutherland had demonstrated Sketchpad, the first use of computer
graphics.  Admiral Grace Murray Hopper built the first compiler for a
computer programming language, allowing programmers to concentrate their
programming effort on the problem being solved rather than arcane
machine details; the rapid development of languages like BASIC, FORTRAN
and COBOL allowed programming to evolve into a discipline as rich and
complex in its own right as computer design, and sparked renewed
interest in the theoretical analysis of algorithms and computability,
based on the pioneering theoretical work of the genius Alan Turing.  In
1968, the NATO Science Committee Conference coined the term <i>software
engineering</i> and the new field was officially born.

<br clear="left"><br>
<A HREF="http://users.ox.ac.uk/~wadh0249/Turing.html">
<img src="gifs/turing.jpg">
</A>
<A HREF="http://www2.bootstrap.org/dce-bio.htm">
<img src="gifs/engelbart.jpg">
</a>
<a href="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Hopper.Danis.html">
<img src="gifs/hopper.gif">
</a>
<br><b>Scientists/Visionaries:</b>: Alan Turing, Doug
Engelbart, Grace Murray Hopper

<br clear="left"><br>
<b>A First:</b>
First visionary glimpses of mouse-and-windows graphical interfaces,
hypertext, and video games.

<br clear="left">
<b>Readings:</b>

<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://www.turing.com/turing/Turing.html">Alan Turing</a>.
       Read all seven bullets in the box marked "To find out more: Read
       a short biography".
  <li> <A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Hopper.Danis.html">Biography
       of Rear Adm. Grace Murray Hopper</A>, who wrote the first
       compiler and found the <A
       HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/Bug.GIF">first actual bug</A>
       in a computer.
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.seas.upenn.edu/~museum/qman/node1.html">ENIAC
       Simulator Manual</A>.  Sadly, the actual simulator isn't yet
       online.  Just skim a few sections, to get the flavor
       of it.  Don't spend more than 10 minutes on this one.
       (<b>Question:</b> Why did we assign this as reading?)
  <li> Vannevar Bush, <A
       HREF="http://www.isg.sfu.ca/~duchier/misc/vbush/">As We May
       Think</A>.  This 1945 article envisioned hypertext systems!  It's
       pretty long, but try to at least get his main vision.
  <li> <b>Scavenger hunt:</b> "People don't realize that frivolity is the
       gateway to the future, in that most future products don't start
       as necessities but as toys." Who said this and what well-known
       computer game company did he start?
  <li> <A HREF="http://www2.bootstrap.org/dce-bio.htm">Biographical
       sketch of Doug Engelbart</A> (from his <a
       href="http://www2.bootstrap.org/">Bootstrap
       Institute</a>---not the most objective)
  <li> <a HREF="http://www.disney.com/DisneyVideos/ToyStory/about/history/1960s.htm">Advances
       in computer graphics</a> from 
       Disney's history of graphics pages
  <li> <b><a href="software.html">Questions for class discussion</a></b>
</ul>

<b>Trivia, Humor, and Highly Recommended Reading:</b>

<ul>
  <li> <a href="http://www.turing.com/turing/scraptest.html">The Turing
       test</a> for machine intelligence
  <li> April 20, 1997, will be the 40th anniversary of the first
       computer error message: <b>"Comma missing from computed go
       to"</b>, delivered by a FORTRAN compiler.  (Courtesy
       <a href="http://ei.cs.vt.edu">Prof. J.A.N. Lee</a> and IEEE Annals of
       the History of Computing)
  <li> <A HREF="http://ei.cs.vt.edu/~history/humor.html">Bold
       projections</A> about computers and other things, for which the
       speakers would 
       probably prefer <i>not</i> to be remembered.
</ul>

<br clear="left"><hr>
<a name="6">
<h3>"A Computer On Every Desktop": Computing for the Masses (1970-1980)</h3>

A quiet revolution had been brewing since the invention of the solid
state transistor at Bell Labs in 1947 and the subsequent invention of
the <i>integrated circuit</i> by Bob Noyce and Jack Kilby, working
independently and at separate companies.  Cheaper, less power-hungry,
and more reliable than its primitive ancestor the vacuum tube, the IC
transformed the landscape for computer design. Engineer and entrepreneur
Ken Olsen seized the opportunity early, and built the hugely successful Digital
Equipment Corp. around <i>minicomputers</i> that even modest businesses
could afford.  (The fabulously successful PDP-8 is the machine on which
the UNIX operating system was born, and its successor the VAX had sold
more units than any machine in history until the IBM PC.) (??)  But what
really turned the tide at Noyce's newly-formed Intel (for
<b>int</b>egrated <b>el</b>ectronics)was Ted Hoff's invention of the
<i>microprocessor</i>, essentially a complete computer on a single chip
("just add memory").  Now, anyone with a few dollars could buy a
microprocessor and build a small computer.  And build they did: when
Steve Wozniak showed off his contraption to the now-legendary Homebrew
Computer Club in Silicon Valley, his entrepreneurial partner Steve Jobs
knew they had a winner.  The Apple II was not the world's first
microcomputer, but with software wizards Dan Bricklin and Bob
Frankston's revolutionary program VisiCalc, the Apple II was the first
to enjoy success because of a <i>Killer App</i>.  The writing was on the
wall:  "None will survive the attack of the killer micros!"

<br clear="left"><br>

<br><b>Inventors/Entrepreneurs:</b> Marcian E. "Ted" Hoff,
Steve Jobs and Steve Wozniak, Bob Bricklin and Dan Frankston

<br clear="left">
<b>Readings:</b>

<ul>
  <li> <A HREF="http://www.herring.com/mag/issue23/accidental.html">The
       Accidental Entrepreneur</a>: Red Herring's interview with Gordon
       Moore, cofounder of Intel
  <li> <A
       HREF="http://techweb.cmp.com/ebn/25year/25_microprocessors1.html">25
       Years That Changed The World</A> (ode to a microprocessor?)
  <li> ...and companion article <A
       HREF="http://techweb.cmp.com/ebn/25year/25_microprocessors2.html">Who
       Really Invented the Microprocessor</A>
  <li> An even more gung-ho point of view: <A
       HREF="http://www.bionomics.org/text/resource/articles/ar_039.html">The
       Microprocessor Renaissance</A>
  <li> <a href="http://www.stout.demon.co.uk/apple/apple2.html">Woz
       &amp; Jobs: The Early Days</a>
  <li> Home page for the <A
       HREF="http://www.navi.net/apple/homebrew.html">original Homebrew
       Computer Club</A>.  Follow the "Apple Computer" link to read
       about the Apple I.
  <li> <a href="gifs/visicalc.gif">Screen shot</a> of the original
       <i>VisiCalc</i> program, by Dan Bricklin and Rob Frankston
  <li> <a href="masses.html"><b>Questions for class discussion</b></a>
</ul>


<b>Highly recommended optional readings:</b>

<ul>
  <li> <b>Trivium:</b> What percentage of Apple II's were purchased
       solely to run VisiCalc?  Look for the answer <a
       href="http://www.stout.demon.co.uk/apple/apple2.html">here</a>. 
  <li> <b>Scavenger hunt:</b> What was the first personal computer to be
       commercially sold?  (It wasn't the Apple II, and the Apple I was
       never commercially sold)

  <li> The <a href="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/">Intel Museum</a>
       online.  Check out especially the <a
       HREF="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/25anniv/">25th
       Anniversary</a> of the microprocessor, and the <A
       HREF="http://www.intel.com/intel/museum/25anniv/html/iwh/iwh_main.htm">Interact With History</A>
       exhibit, which lets you "relive" the founding of Intel and the
       invention of the microprocessor.

  <li> Our very own <A
       HREF="http://http.cs.berkeley.edu/Soda/soda/individuals/Wozniak_S.html">
       Steve Wozniak!</A>
</ul>


