@d63 30
a92 29
<a href="http://www.computer-museum.org/collections/hollerith.html"><img 
src="gifs/hollpunch.gif" align="right"></a>
The U.S. of the late 1800's was the world's industrial and economic
leader, with a laissez-faire capitalist ambience that encouraged an
unprecedented wave of innovation and invention....and a population
exploding so rapidly that census tabulation could barely be finished in
time for the next census.  It was in this atmosphere that the energetic
and entrepreneurial
<a href="http://www.invent.org/book/book-text/57.html">Herman
Hollerith</a> patented his punch-card reader and
tabulating machine, which the U.S. Government used for the 1890 and 1900
censuses and which made  Hollerith a millionaire.  (<b>Scavenger
hunt:</b> What year was the last U.S. Census to use punch-card
technology, and what replaced the punch cards after that?)
<br clear="left">
Not long after, among the calculator builders improving on the
work of their nineteenth-century forefathers, we find one who would be
pivotal: Konrad Zuse's machines could be programmed using paper tapes,
and operated using the binary (base 2) number system and the logic
invented by George Boole in 1854.  Unfortunately for Zuse, another
machine stole the show: the Mark I, built at Harvard and IBM under the
direction of Howard Aiken, the ultimate mechanical
computer...and a technological dead end.  For in heartland Iowa and
eastern Pennsylvania, the ideas behind the nearest predecessor to today's
electronic computer were being developed.   The inventors would
deliver to the military the next-generation electronic computer and
launch a new industry, only to be overtaken by the company that would
become synonymous with computers, the descendant of Hollerith's
CTR Company: <a href="http://www.ibm.com/">IBM</a>.<p>
