<h3>ENIAC and Univac: The Computer Is Born (1940-1955)</h3>
d133 22
a154 20
By 1937, America's eventual involvement in World War II seemed
inevitable.  But the fastest available computing device, the analog
Differential Analyzer invented by MIT's visionary Vannevar Bush, took
nearly a month to compute ballistic trajectory tables; so the Army,
desperate for faster computers, awarded a contract in 1943 to the
University of Pennsylvania's Moore School of Engineering, where
little-known recent faculty hire John Mauchly and 21-year-old lab
assistant J. Presper Eckert had proposed a high-speed vacuum-tube
calculating machine.  Working against the opinion of the nation's most
influential researchers and military strategists, Eckert and Mauchly's
team produced ENIAC (Electronic Numerical Integrator And Calculator),
the first general-purpose electronic digital computer, ushering in the
computer age.  Little did they know that the Eckert-Mauchly Computer
Company would become the patriarch of a family tree marred by the most
bitter and protracted patent feud in computer history.  At issue:
Mauchly's conversations with John Vincent Atanasoff, an Iowa State
professor who had been playing with vacuum-tube binary circuits;
engineering dean Paul
Brainerd's ideas about patent
policies for Moore School research; and the unofficial early "evangelism"
