@d107 36
a142 20
In 1937, America's eventual involvement in World War II seemed
inevitable.  But the fastest available computing device, the
Differential Analyzer invented by MIT's visionary Vannevar Bush, took nearly a
month to compute ballistic trajectory tables; the Army, desperate for
faster computers, awarded a contract to the University of Pennsylvania's
Moore School of Engineering, where little-known recent faculty hire John
Mauchly and lab assistant J. Presper Eckert had proposed a high-speed
vacuum-tube calculating machine.  Working against the opinion of the
nation's highest-profile and most brilliant researchers and strategists,
Eckert and Mauchly's team produced ENIAC (Electronic Numerical
Integrator And Calculator), ushering in the computer age.  Little did
Mauchly know that the Eckert-Mauchly Computer Company would become the
patriarch of a family tree that included the most bitter and protracted
patent-feud sibling rivalries in computer history.  At issue: Mauchly's
conversations with John Vincent Atanasoff, an Iowa State professor who
had been playing with vacuum-tube binary circuits; Paul Brainerd's (Dean
of Engineering at the Moore School) ideas about patent policies for
University research; and the unofficial early "evangelism" publication
describing stored-program computers by brilliant and flamboyant
mathematician John von Neumann.
